title: Cognition, Age, and RaPamycin Effectiveness - DownregulatIon of thE mTor Pathway (CARPE DIEM)
description_brief: Evaluation of central nervous system penetration of orally administered Rapamune (RAPA) in older adults with Mild Cognitive Impairment (MCI) or early Alzheimer's disease (AD) and investigate associated safety, tolerability, target engagement, cognition, and functional status as initial proof-of-concept study
description_detailed: This study is an open-label pilot study of orally administered RAPA to measure its target engagement in Cerebrospinal Fluid (CSF) and blood, and to establish the feasibility and safety of RAPA treatment in older adults with MCI and early stage AD as initial proof-of-concept for a larger Phase 2 clinical trial.

explanation_target: Reason: The trial tests orally administered Rapamune (brand name for sirolimus / rapamycin), an mTOR inhibitor, in people with MCI or early AD to evaluate CNS penetration, safety/tolerability, target engagement and cognitive/functional outcomes — indicating an intervention that targets a disease-related pathway (mTOR/autophagy) rather than a symptomatic-only cognitive enhancer. citeturn0search6turn0search2turn1search7

Act (extraction): Key details from the trial description — Title: CARPE DIEM (Cognition, Age, and RaPamycin Effectiveness - DownregulatIon of thE mTor Pathway); population: older adults with MCI or early AD; intervention: orally administered Rapamune (sirolimus); primary experimental aim: assess CNS (CSF) penetration and target engagement plus safety, tolerability, and preliminary cognitive/functional effects. citeturn0search6

Act (drug information): Rapamune is the marketed formulation of sirolimus (rapamycin), an orally administered small-molecule inhibitor that binds FKBP12 and inhibits the mechanistic target of rapamycin (mTOR). It is an approved drug for immunosuppression and other indications (prescribing information). citeturn0search2turn0search8

Reflect (classification): Sirolimus/rapamycin is a small-molecule mTOR inhibitor that targets a molecular pathway (mTOR) implicated in AD pathophysiology (autophagy, protein clearance, neuroinflammation, BBB integrity). Because it is a small molecule acting on disease-relevant biology (not a biologic like an antibody, and not solely a symptomatic cognitive enhancer or neuropsychiatric treatment), the correct category is: disease-targeted small molecule. citeturn0search7turn1search4turn1search2
